@xiguantiaozhan Sorry for the late reply. I guess what @ijuma suggested was just having something like below:
```
trait KafkaControllerListner(controller: KafkaController) {
  def isActive = controller.isActive
}
```

All the other listeners can extends this trait (in Scala a class can extends multiple classes)

I've created a test for this condition but I'm not happy with the way it's implemented.
Just take a look at it:
```java
    @Test
    public void testExceptionThrownWhenFileRecordsAreTruncatedDuringWrite() throws IOException {
        File file = tempFile();
        FileChannel channel = new RandomAccessFile(file, "r").getChannel();
        GatheringByteChannel destination = null;

        FileRecords fieldRecordsPartialMock = EasyMock.partialMockBuilder(FileRecords.class)
                .withConstructor(file, channel, 0, Integer.MAX_VALUE, false)
                .addMockedMethod("sizeInBytes")
                .createNiceMock();

        EasyMock.expect(fieldRecordsPartialMock.sizeInBytes()).andReturn(42);
        EasyMock.replay(fieldRecordsPartialMock);

        try {
            fieldRecordsPartialMock.writeTo(destination, 0, 1);
            fail("Should throw KafkaException");
        } catch (KafkaException e) {
            // expected
        }
    }
```
The underlying behaviour relies on multithreaded condition and for current implementation it's not as simple to test as one would like to (which might be the reason why it wasn't tested in the beginning).
With my current understanding of Kafka's internals I don't feel competent enough to refactor the implementation (I'm also not convinced that it should be refactored solely for making testing that condition easier).
I wouldn't like to add this test to the test suite because it does a poor job at documenting the scenario due to using a partial mock (the only way to do it for current implementation without unnecessarily tying to the implementation) and requiring multiple values not related to the tested behaviour.
Moreover I don't see further changes coming to this piece of code that might be covered by that test.
Maybe you have a better way to test this scenario?
